		<div class="comment-text">
			<p>When the ancient astronomers derived the v^2r = K equation, they had only two orbital systems to study, and no understanding of WHY the value of K should be unique to each system.</p>
<p>Newton showed that K is proportional to the mass of the parent body (Sun, Earth, Jupiter, epsilon Eridani, &#8230;), thereby providing the underlying reason for the variation.</p>
<p>Whether G is a fundamental or a derived constant is a debateable point, I admit. Using Einstein&#8217;s formulation gives a slightly higher value of G near very massive bodies, in fact. Nevertheless, to make the gravitation law an equation requires some constant of proportionality.</p>
