<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="comment-845">
	<div>

		<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/676ff6cf530af46c0a404abd399a464c?s=50&amp;d=&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' />

		<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/wheatdogg/gravity-deniers-and-the-gravity-of-ignorance/?replytocom=845#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-845", "845", "respond", "186")'>Reply</a>

		<span class="comment-author">
			<a href='http://wgods.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Wilhelm Godschalk</a>
		</span>
		
		<span class="comment-date-link">
			<a href="http://www.computernewbie.info/wheatdogg/gravity-deniers-and-the-gravity-of-ignorance/#comment-845">
				Aug 15,2006 
				6:41 pm
			</a>
		</span>				

		 
		
		

		<div class="comment-text">
			<p>Wheatdogg wrote:<br />
<i>&#8220;I am perplexed by Wilhelm’s complaint that physicists have “decreed” that there are attractive or repulsive forces, or that orbiting electrons should not radiate EM waves. We are not telling nature what to do. We are trying to explain what nature is doing.&#8221;</i></p>
<p>Of course I agree fully with the last two sentences.  My complaint was baed on the idea that physics (just like other sciences) should be built up step by step.  If a new phenomenon is discovered, we should try to explain it on the basis of what we already know.  If an assumption is made that casually throws away the laws that we established previously, i.e., just assuming they are not valid in this particular case, then I call that a &#8220;decree&#8221;.  Maybe not a diplomatic way of expressing myself, but I learned my diplomacy from Nikita Khrushev (we shared a birthday, besides).<br />
Examples: 1. On of the basic laws is the first law of thermodynamics.  Energy is neither created nor destroyed.  We also know that energy can be used to perform work, lower entropy, or produce heat.  Then, if someone proposes a force that performs work but doesn&#8217;t use up energy, according to my view, that force has been created by decree.<br />
2. We know that positive and negative charges attract each other.  If we look at Rutherford&#8217;s model, why don&#8217;t the electrons just fall into the nucleus?<br />
We have to dive into quantum mechanics, to be able to calculate the electron density at each point, to find our answer.  But after we do that, have we really understood why?<br />
The reactive force of a shelf preventing an object from falling to the floor is another example.  Here we have to create a second force, just to explain the first force (gravity) we have postulated.  It&#8217;s just like lies: After the first lie, you have to come up with numerous secundary lies, just to back up the first one.</p>
<p><i>&#8220;How then can we, within this model, explain why solid objects do not pass through one another?&#8221;I/I&gt;<br />
This model purports not to break any existing laws of physics.  One of the first I ever learned was that two bodies can never occupy the same space at the same time.  That&#8217;s what keeps the student from falling through the bench.  We also have the observation that atoms cannot be pushed closer together than a certain limit, due to the Born repulsion.  But we don&#8217;t really know where that force comes from either.<br />
As long as we are sitting on the ground, or on a chair, we&#8217;ll just keep on moving along with the earth&#8217;s surface.  If we try to float freely, the earth will catch up with us.<br />
And yes &#8211; According to the expansion theory, the sun will expand even faster than the earth, and we&#8217;ll be toast one day.  Just be patient.</p>
<p>It&#8217;s perfectly OK if the expansion theory doesn&#8217;t appeal to you.  It does to me, more so than the classical model.  But you&#8217;re right: We should look for ways to base predictions on it, so it can be tested.</p>
<p>Wheatdogg, you asked a while back where to find how Newton used the model of the boy swinging a rock on a string, to arrive at his gravitational equation.  Of course he never mentioned a boy with a rock, but you can see how he just pulled  the principle of a centripetal force out of his hat.  There is an English translation of that particular chapter of the Principia.  You can find it here:</p>
<p>   <a href="http://members.tripod.com/~gravitee/booki2.htm" rel="nofollow">http://members.tripod.com/~gravitee/booki2.htm</a></i></p>

			
		</div>

	</div>
