		<div class="comment-text">
			<p><i>&#8220;Godschalk, compare the mathematical content of McCutcheon’s book with the physics that he hopes to replace.&#8221;</i></p>
<p>Yes, McCutcheon is indeed a little skimpy on the mathematics.  He&#8217;s an engineer, so I&#8217;m sure he could have poured on more math.  But he also wants to sell his book, so he opted for a more popular form.  Think of Gibbs, who wrote up his original formulation of Thermodynamics in such an abstract form that it was ignored.  Others, after him, had to re-invent it.<br />
But the physics he hopes to replace is not all peaches and cream either.  Scientists who have launched an invalid theory (and those who believe strongly in it) often resort to giving complicated renditions of details that only bear a distant relationship to the central theme.  That way, most people don&#8217;t understand the discussion anymore.  And those who do are being led away from the main flaws.  I see that happen a lot.  In physics, the unwary reader is treated to some high-powered mathematics.  In biology, critics are buried in an alfabet soup of genes and &#8220;special occult cofactors&#8221;.<br />
I don&#8217;t eschew mathematics (on the contrary), but when a little kid or a dumb blonde asks me: &#8220;What is an atom?&#8221;  I don&#8217;t scribble formulas on a napkin, but I try to create a mental picture of it, that is easy to understand, very much like my old highschool teacher did.  The yeahbuts come later.</p>
<p><i>&#8220;If we relied on “common sense” we would still think that the Sun circles the Earth.&#8221;</i></p>
<p>That would be awkward, but not disastrous.  The geocentric model worked fairly well for centuries.  It had its problems, like planets that went retrograde for some time during their orbiting cycle.  But was it wrong?  Not really.  It just looked at planetary motions from another point of view (in a most literal way). The heliocentric model worked much better, because it described the motions of the planets in a more understandable way.  In other words: The math was simpler.</p>
<p><i>&#8220;McCutcheon’s claim that modern physics cannot explain fridge magnets is just plain stupid.&#8221;</i></p>
<p>I must confess that I never understood the fridge magnets, Chris.  And I suspect that there are others just like me.  So why don&#8217;t you explain it to us, on the basis of modern physics?</p>

			
		</div>

	</div>
