<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1" id="comment-852">
	<div>

		<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/0e204d0b20d6be4e10070fe05bf35c34?s=50&amp;d=&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' />

		<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/wheatdogg/gravity-deniers-and-the-gravity-of-ignorance/?replytocom=852#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm("comment-852", "852", "respond", "186")'>Reply</a>

		<span class="comment-author">
			<a href='http://www.wheatdogg.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>wheatdogg</a>
		</span>
		
		<span class="comment-date-link">
			<a href="http://www.computernewbie.info/wheatdogg/gravity-deniers-and-the-gravity-of-ignorance/#comment-852">
				Aug 17,2006 
				9:17 pm
			</a>
		</span>				

		 
		
		

		<div class="comment-text">
			<p>I am beginning to feel like a charter member of the Ike Newton Fan Club here, but this remark just plain irks me: </p>
<p><em>&#8230; you can see how he just pulled the principle of a centripetal force out of his hat.</em></p>
<p>Now, what annoys me about this remark, Wilhelm &#8212; aside from the scorn dripping from the characters &#8212; is the implication that Newton arbitrarily invoked a centripetal force to fill some sort of gap in his logic. In fact, a centripetal force is a necessary consequence of the first and second laws of motion. Remember, Newton proposed a flat Euclidean space, so the first law requires  objects to follow straight-line paths in the absence of a net force. The second law states that a non-zero net force will result in an acceleration, which could include a change in direction as well as speed.</p>
<p>So, for Newton&#8217;s mechanics to be logical and self-consistent, there must be some force that points to the center of a curved path, diverting the object from its straight-line path. Proposing same and deriving the equation for it can hardly be called, &#8220;pulling it out his hat.&#8221; </p>
<p>Not quite so irksome is this rejoinder:</p>
<blockquote><p>The geocentric model worked fairly well for centuries. It had its problems, like planets that went retrograde for some time during their orbiting cycle. But was it wrong? Not really.</p></blockquote>
<p>Its &#8220;wrongness&#8221; would depend on who was judging it. William of Ockham, had he investigated the Ptolemaic model of circles, deferents and epicycles needed to plot retrograde motion, would have rejected the model out of hand, as it was much too complicated. The King of Spain, Alfonso el sabio, reportedly remarked that if the creator had consulted Alfonso, he would have suggested a simpler universe.</p>
<p>The Ptolemaic model did not work all that well in the long term. In the short term, say a few hundred years, the 90 deferents and epicycles required to calculate the positions of the planets and Sun worked reasonably well. The Arabs called Ptolemy&#8217;s work, &#8220;the greatest,&#8221; or <em>Al Magest</em>, since it was so accurate. But those calculations, based on an inaccurate notion of planetary orbits, were merely approximations, and the error introduced with each successive cycle became quite alarming by the 1500s. The Julian calendar by that time was almost 11 days out of sync with the motion of the Sun through the equinoxes and solstices. </p>
<p>The Copernican model, which William and Alfonso may have liked better, was simpler and more accurate, though still not perfect. I would argue, though admittedly from a modern perspective, that the Copernican model was more common-sensical than Ptolemy&#8217;s because it <strong>was</strong> both accurate <strong>and</strong> simple. And it permitted the Catholic Church to develop a new calendar, which we still use today.</p>
<p>This whole notion of the &#8220;rightness&#8221; of a model or theory is a tricky one. We could argue that with more accurate measurements of time and position we could in fact refine the Ptolemaic system to give results as good as or perhaps better than Copernicus&#8217;s or even Kepler&#8217;s. The question is, would we want to? Ptolemy&#8217;s system lacked any sort of explanation why retrograde motion should happen and why the planets should bother following these ridiculously complex orbits. Copernicus was able to explain retrograde motion more succinctly, but of course neither he nor Kepler could offer an explanation why the planets should follow circular or elliptical paths.</p>
<p>Newton&#8217;s law of universal gravitation, with its inverse-square relationship of distance and force, requires that planetary orbits be one of the conic sections (Newton worked out the derivation with the calculus), which are the circle, the ellipse, the parabola and the hyperbola. So Newton was able to offer an  explanation for why Kepler&#8217;s first law should be true for all orbiting bodies. Likewise, he was able to verify mathematically the second law of equal areas in equal times, and the third law relation of the proportionality of orbital-period-squared to average-radius-cubed. </p>
<p>Now, on that basis alone, I would say Newton&#8217;s model was right. It was certainly more elegant than Ptolemy&#8217;s, but perhaps not as elegant as Aristotle&#8217;s, which of course was just plain wrong.</p>

			
		</div>

	</div>
</li><!-- #comment-## -->
